<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-008-073 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 593 568</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Nov 25 1991 v10 n24 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Military tries to make up for Ada engineer shortage. (softwareengineers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schwartz, Karen D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The military needs software engineers and experiences difficultyretaining the ones that it has.andP;  Two services have master's degreeprograms that focus on the programming language Ada: the AirForce's Institute of Technology (AFIT) has an 18-month course, andthe Army's Center for Software Engineering offers a two-yearprogram.andP;  The Air Force program accepts officers, usually with therank of captain, or civilians with a rating of GS-12 or higher;the Army's program accepts civilians just out of college.andP;  Thereis a pressing need for software engineers trained in Ada, andthese programs help to supply them, but the services havedifficulty retaining the trained engineers that the programsproduce.andP;  The Army does not require its graduates to stay in themilitary, and the Air Force only requires a commitment of threeyears service for every year of school.andP;  Various new incentivesare being considered.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software engineeringMilitaryUnited States. Department of DefenseUnited States. Air Force. Institute of TechnologyUnited States. Army. Center for Software EngineeringADAContract ProgrammersComputer Education.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>